                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1418" type="given" value="PHILIP"></interp>PHILIP ROSE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to a pawnbroker in Holborn. I produce a swing-glass and some cotton, pawned with me, on the 24th of December, by Henry Allshorn.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410405-name-1419" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1419" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1419" type="surname" value="CREED"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1419" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>STEPHEN CREED</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 200.) I went to search the resi<lb></lb>dence of James Edward Allshorn—I saw him throw a paper parcel out of his pocket behind the door—I picked it up, and it contained seven dupli<lb></lb>cates; and, on searching him, I found the duplicate of the seven yards and a half of cotton pawned at Richmond.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410405-name-1420" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1420" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1420" type="surname" value="IRELAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1420" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM IRELAND</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City police-constable, No.</hi> 130.) I found the du<lb></lb>plicate of the other cotton and the glass on Henry Allshorn.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410405-name-1421" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1421" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1421" type="surname" value="PIGGOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410405-name-1421" type="given" value="FREDERICK"></interp>FREDERICK PIGGOTT</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> When James William Allshorn was locked up, I asked him if there was any thing else he had taken—he said, "Yes, there is the glass, and the other furniture, that is all"—he was going on to state about some money he had kept from me, when the po<lb></lb>liceman came up, and advised him to say no more.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">John William Allshorn.</hi> He came and held out an inducement to me that he would be as lenient as possible, and he gave me two hours to con<lb></lb>sider of it. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> No, I told him if I found more property, it might make me more severe—I said, "You had better tell me where it is, it may save me trouble"—he had told me of the glass before, and said he did not pledge it himself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">James Edward Allshorn's Defence.</hi> On the 23rd of December I was in London; my son Henry told me be could make me a present of some cotton, to cover some chairs that I had, and I accepted it, not questioning but that he had purchased it, and the glass too, as he said he had.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
